      "h1": "Oil vs cream – when skin wants less, not more",
      "lead": "Face oil vs face cream is not a loyalty test. It’s about how skin behaves: how much water it loses, how much lipids it needs, and what actually sits well on top. Sometimes oil wins. Sometimes a cream or emulsion is simply the more practical move.",
      "problemTitle": "When does oil beat cream?",
      "problemBody": "<p>A face cream is usually an <strong>emulsion</strong>: water and oil held together with emulsifiers. That makes it easy to spread, but also more complex. A face oil is simpler. No water phase, fewer moving parts, and often a more direct feel on skin when you want less friction and a lighter routine.</p><p>The key is the <strong>occlusive</strong> effect: how well a product slows water loss. Oils can reduce transepidermal water loss effectively, but they do not add water themselves. Creams do both: they can deliver water, emollients and a barrier in one step. That is why cream often wins when skin is truly dry, while oil is enough when skin mainly needs comfort and protection.</p><p>Absorption is the wrong obsession. Skin does not need to “drink” everything you apply. What matters is how the product behaves: whether it settles quickly, sits well under a makeup-layer, or turns the face too shiny. The mainstream rule of “always choose the lightest texture” rarely survives contact with real life. Skin is not a spreadsheet.</p>",
