      "metaDescription": "Physical vs chemical spf: how filters differ in feel, protection and what actually suits your skin.",
      "kicker": "Sun Care",
      "h1": "Physical vs chemical spf – not the fight it’s made out to be",
      "lead": "Sunscreen has become a small religion, but your skin mostly cares about one thing: do you actually wear it. Physical vs chemical spf is less about good versus bad and more about filters, texture and how likely you are to use it every day. The nuance is bigger than slogans like “reef safe” and “natural”.",
      "problemTitle": "So what really separates the filters?",
      "problemBody": "<p>Physical sunscreen usually relies on mineral filters like <strong>zinc oxide</strong> and titanium dioxide. They sit on the skin and scatter, plus partly reflect, UV radiation. Chemical filters absorb UV and convert the energy into heat; some formulas use a <strong>filter-cascade</strong>, where several filters work together for broader coverage and better stability.</p><p>This is where the debate tends to get messy. Mineral sounds safer, chemical sounds suspicious, but the reality is more practical: both can work very well when they’re properly formulated and applied in enough product. Studies also suggest that differences in protection often come down more to application, reapplication and film evenness than to the label on the front.</p><p>The big downside with many mineral formulas is the feel: a white cast, a dry finish, or a tendency to cling to beard hair and pores. Chemical filters can sting the eyes, feel lighter, yet still irritate sensitive skin. So the real question is not who wins on paper, but which texture you can actually live with on a sunny Tuesday.</p>",
      "tipsTitle": "How to choose without overthinking it",
